context: At high altitudes, Neptune's atmosphere is <a0_0><b5_0>80% hydrogen and 19% helium<b5_0/><a0_0/>. A trace amount of methane is also present. Prominent absorption bands of methane exist at <a1_0><b6_0>wavelengths above 600 nm<b6_0/><a1_0/>, in the red and infrared portion of the spectrum. As with <b8_0>Uranus<b8_0/>, this <a2_0><b7_0>absorption of red light by the atmospheric methane<b7_0/><a2_0/> is part of what gives Neptune its blue hue, although Neptune's vivid azure differs from Uranus's milder <a4_0><b9_0>cyan<b9_0/><a4_0/>. Because Neptune's atmospheric methane content is similar to that of <a3_0>Uranus<a3_0/>, some unknown atmospheric constituent is thought to contribute to Neptune's colour.
